english:
  title: The Southern Inscription
  author: Kim Siheup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Cultivate your virtue with diligence, pursue your strength with vigor—
    Let night flow into day and dawn continue into dusk.
    Study the ancients and broaden your learning;
    When duty calls, act with precision.

    Do not chase after wealth and rank with grasping hands,
    Nor let poverty and lowliness cloud your spirit.
    Follow the will of Yi Yin,
    Emulate the learning of Yan Hui.

    Though you dwell in a humble cottage on woven straw,
    Never neglect the nation's burden from the halls of state.
    Though you wear a tattered hat and threadbare robes,
    Forget not your tongue's power to offer counsel.

    Properity and hardship, acclaim and obscurity—
    These the heavens may determine.
    But loyalty, faith, virtue, and righteousness
    Rest truly in human hands.

    Be not content with yourself;
    Thrice daily examine your own conduct.
    Avoid the flattery and excess of base desires,
    That you might receive the five blessings of the Perfect Mean.

    Ponder this truth well—
    I inscribe it on the southern wall.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Yin was a legendary sage and minister of the Shang dynasty, known for his moral integrity and devoted service.
  - key: ''
    value: Yan Hui was Confucius's most beloved disciple, revered for his virtue and humble pursuit of learning despite poverty.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'five blessings' (五福) in Chinese cosmology are longevity, wealth, health, virtue, and a peaceful death.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Perfect Mean' (皇極) refers to the supreme principle of harmony and balance in governance and personal conduct.
